text.tspan: I Master to Earn the Highest Salaries?
Salary (ARS as of 2020) - Source: Sysarmy Survey

tspan.tspan: To this end, we cure the dataset from SysArmy removing outliers salaries below Q.25 - 1.5 IQR and higher
than Q.75 + 1.5 IQR (25% and 75% quartiles and Inter-quartile range). We also keep the 30 most frequently
used languages on the survey. Each language is considered
independently (i.e., a single entry with multiple
languages is considered separately). The result is as follows.
We care about the probability of earning the highest salaries (asuming these are within the topmost 90% of
the survey entries), given that the employee is coding a specific programming language. In other words, we
compute the conditional probability X in which an employee can earn a salary within the 90-percentile of the
best salaries given that he/she masters the language Li. This is P(X|Li) = P(X∩Li)/P(Li), for each language i
part of the most frequently used languages.
This is a technical report about the relation of salaries and programming languages used among software
industry employees in Argentina as of 2020. The source of the dataset used for the analysis is a SysArmy
The analysis performed shows that coding in Scala unlocks the maxiumum chance (36%) of earning the topmost salaries within
Argentina, considering theis dataset from 2020. We obseve that Scala programmers are 8% more likely to earn salaries within the
90-percentile. Modern languages such as Go, Ruby and Python are above 12% of probability of earning the highest salaries.
classical languages such as C and C++ are at the bottom of the list, suggesting the lowest salaries among the samples.
